# Markdown Timestamp Update Rule

## Context
- Applies to all markdown files
- Updates timestamp after main title
- Ensures consistent documentation tracking
- Maintains proper spacing for readability

## Requirements
- Add or update timestamp after main title (H1)
- Format: Updated: YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm
- EXECUTE (do not paste) the timestamp command:
  ```powershell
  # EXECUTE this command, do not paste it as text!
  Get-Date -Format "yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm"
  ```
  ```bash
  # EXECUTE this command, do not paste it as text!
  date "+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M"
  ```
- One empty line after H1 title
- One empty line after timestamp
- Preserve existing content
- Insert timestamp if not present
- Update timestamp if present

## Examples
<example>
# Document Title

*Updated: 2024-03-21 20:45*  # This should be actual output from command execution

Content starts here...
</example>

<example type="invalid">
# Document Title
*Updated: $(Get-Date -Format "yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm")*  # WRONG: Command text pasted instead of executed!
Content starts here...

# Document Title
*Updated: date "+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M"*  # WRONG: Command text pasted instead of executed!
Content starts here...
</example>

## Critical Rules
- ALWAYS update timestamp on save
- ALWAYS place timestamp after H1 title with one empty line before and after
- ALWAYS use format: *Updated: YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm*
- ALWAYS EXECUTE system date command to generate timestamp - DO NOT paste the command text!
- NEVER remove or modify other content
- NEVER add timestamp if no H1 exists
- NEVER manually write timestamps
- NEVER paste the command itself - EXECUTE it and use the output!
